HEADWORD: Shabby
<hw>Shab"by</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Shabbier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Shabbiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[See <er>Shab</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Scabby</er>, and <er>Scab</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Torn or worn to rage; poor; mean; ragged.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wearing <qex>shabby</qex> coats and dirty shirts.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Clothed with ragged, much worn, or soiled
garments.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The dean was so <xex>shabby</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mean; paltry; despicable; <as>as, <ex>shabby</ex>
treatment</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Very <xex>shabby</xex> fellows.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shabrack</ent>⟦br⟧
